The paper discusses the design and testing of a course selection tool for undergraduates, which involves human-computer interaction (HCI) and user-centered design principles. Therefore, cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also touches on issues related to advising, career paths, and software tools, which could fall under cs.CY (Computers and Society), cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science), and cs.CL (Computation and Language). Finally, the paper mentions the limitations of software tools and the importance of in-person advising, which could be relevant to cs.SE (Software Engineering).
